The problem is trust. Do you trust the people you share the database with? Er ... server It's kinda funny you mention that. Well biggest one I can think of is doing something stupid like $_GET['filename'] and $_GET['filename'] being the full path. Where $_GET['file_id'] would be much safer, then doing a lookup. There are so many people I've seen do http://whatever.com/index.php?page=filename.php then do an include_once ($_GET['filename']); It's a big security risk if you ask me. camcorder: like all of them? That's the best way to do it when dealing with a database. camcorder: I can't think of one off the top of my head. The only thing I think you might be able to do is a glob on your session's temp dir. When they log in set the last_time_logged_in to NOW(); Then - your last query on the page - update where last_time_logged_in <= "'.date('Y-d-m h:?:?',strtotime('-30 min')).'" camcorder: Are you using a mysql? I'm just saying 30 minutes ... you could set it to 5 minutes. OR if you really obsessive, have some sort of countdown script that 'pings' your server ever x minutes. Something in AJAX. ... I'm up to the challenge ... and board ... I think I'll write a quick script that does it.

I'm curious.  I'm fairly new to PHP and I've been developing a site that connects to a MySQL database.  So far the only way that I've determined to be able to connect to the database is to store the username and password in a file in plaintext.  This seems like a bad idea to me.  Is there some other way that I'm not seeing or thinking of?  The only altername idea I had was to encrypt the username and password, and hard-code the decryption ke ys into the program, which seems to not really be much better off than just using plain text.  Any more experienced PHP developers care to chime in on this? yeah, so far the best thing I've been able to think of is to tell the server admin that the site is going to to just make sure to get the permissions set right so that nobody can read the config file that has the database username and password, and to make sure to set the database up such that compromising that database username and password won't compromise any other data luckily, nothing that sensitive is being stored in the database for this project, but it just sort of bothered me as a potential security hole thanks CyaNox I couldn't actually hard code the connection information into the code, because the people the code is for said basically "we don't want to have to ever edit the code", so I put the connection info in an ini file and wrote a simple program to allow them to configure it without having to edit code yeah, what I was thinking of doing is having two config files, one that is the actual config file, and another file that tells the program where to find the config file, then set up an install scrip that will install the php files and put the actual config file in /etc/sysconfig but allow the admin to actually put the config file wherever they want I suppose with a little bit of more complex scripting I could just edit the code that looks for the file, but I'm no wiz at shell scripting either ...yeah, I didn't think of that just kind of thinking about ideas aloud well, the server is owned by the people I'm doign the site for, and it's on site and not a colo.  What I don't entirely trust is that, given my relative lack of experience, that I do not have some glaring security holes in my own code - although I have tried to follow best practices and have done a fair bit of testing- and I'm trying to figgure out how to best mitigate any potential problems my inexperience may have caused. yeah, I'm not specifically getting any files from the system.  I tried to avoid sending data through $_GET as much as possible, and I tried to make sure that everything I sent (through post or get) was checked for validity, and I used mysql_real_escape_string on every variable that was included in an sql query. camcorder, I would think the best way would be to use either a database table (probably slow) or write to a file the user name or some other identification when a user logs in, then remove them when the log out well, I'm going to take off for a bit.  Thanks for the help and pointers all

Why do you need a standardised API for implementing pretty-printers? Isn't it fine to just have a standalone pretty-printing tool that uses private APIs of a specific implementation? Getting an implementation to expose a private API sounds like far less effort than getting every implementation to expose a public API How can it not be true? af3dbf37599986db770f1b7851827890: sure. but it might be better to put multiple <section>s in an <aside id="sidebar">‚Ä¶ Hixie: re: the 2005 Web Authoring Stats, I‚Äôd be interested in the data for the current web. It‚Äôs been almost 5 years, so the differences would be interesting Hixie: Also it‚Äôd be interesting to specifically check for class names that might indicate a page made with best practices ‚Äî things like clearfix, group, amp ‚Äî and see if the code from that small fraction of pages is different to the norm Hixie: finally if you really want to blue-sky it I bet www-style would love something similar for CSS Hixie: oh, sitename as id on body (eg <body id="whatwg-org">) would be another indicator af3dbf37599986db770f1b7851827890: <aside> can contain other sectioning elements, such as multiple <section> elements the thing to ask yourself is whether the content in the <aside> is related to the section/article it‚Äôs in, and whether the content is not essential to the understanding of the main content aah if it‚Äôs unrelated to the main content (which is presumably in <article), then in an <aside> that‚Äôs a sibling of <article> (ie an <aside> that‚Äôs related to <body>) may be the way to go <body>‚Ä¶<article></article><aside></aside></body> is a page-level aside (applies to the page)‚Ä¶ <body>‚Ä¶<article><aside></aside></article></body> the aside applies to the article content you can see an example of a page aside in the second code sample here: http://oli.jp/2009/html5-structure4/#article-page at the top of that page the coding style pulldown is in an aside that‚Äôs in <article>, because it‚Äôs related to the article (not the page) heh, it gets easier to give a simple example, you know how in HTML 4 <address> was only for the contact info for the page right? in HTML5 you can also use <address> in an <article>, and when you do it becomes contact info for the article only. both elements are scoped by their context ‚Äî what they apply to depends on what they‚Äôre inside Think Russian nested dolls‚Ä¶ in cute little angle brackets ;-) af3dbf37599986db770f1b7851827890: np. if you have probs or questions this is a pretty good place to ask. after that check www.html5doctor.com, www.diveintohtml5.com, or even www.oli.jp ;-) af3dbf37599986db770f1b7851827890: (conflict of interest statement: I‚Äôm writing for two of them :) )

you can't use :1 interfaces just use eth1 eth1:1 doesn't really exist MrSako: check for other rules above that one MrSako: looks fine to me is the HTTP server on the same host as this firewall? do any of the rules have nonzero counter in iptables-save -c? run iptables-save -c look at the counters of the rules (stuff in []) ok... it should be working then actually, you should have a state rule in there MrSako: iptables -A INPUT -m state --state RELATED,ESTABLISHED -j ACCEPT Artimus: block it in FORWARD; -i eth1 -o eth2 -j DROP that's an example... oh you'd have to use IPs -i eth1 -o eth1 -s IPRANGE1 -d IPRANGE2 that'll work are the pings even going through the firewall? they might be pinging directly by pinging one another... I think linux will send ICMP reroutes not sure - try a packet sniffer to see if they're going through (of course, those ranges can ping one another if you have a 255.255.0.0 netmask, but I was assuming /24) that's wrong hmm. try modprobe ipt_state what kernel? uname -a that'll tell you the kernel does /proc/net/ip_conntrack exist? modprobe ip_conntrack does /proc/net/ip_conntrack exist now? :/ do you have an ip_conntrack.ko? it'd be in /lib/modules looks like you have a problem with your kernel unless centos hides its modules somewhere else... did you compile your kernel, or use a package? can you convince the owner to put conntrack into the kernel? That'd be the best solution otherwise, you'll have to outgoing connections back in manually /proc/net/ip_conntrack is a file created by the kernel, keeping a table of connections I wasn't interested in the contents, only the existance if it exists, ip_conntrack is in the kernel /lib/modules has the kernel modules for the running kernel for example, here, I have /lib/modules/2.6.17+g/kernel/net/netfilter/nf_conntrack.ko

b8810fee2f4a71f849f3f7409546d1d9: Which restriction are you referring to? b8810fee2f4a71f849f3f7409546d1d9: Ah Seems a really bad idea in terms of forward-compatibility (At least one implementation (rdfQuery) throws a fatal error if you have a rel keyword that's not on the list, which can't be good) b8810fee2f4a71f849f3f7409546d1d9: Compliance doesn't require implementations to throw fatal errors, just to ignore the value, as far as I can tell will refrain from making any suggestions on handling rel="alternate stylesheet" similarly to how HTML5 microdata handles it (as a single token) also refrains from commenting on rel="STYLESHEET" etc, which seemingly won't be accepted by an RDFa processor Regardless of where valid rel values are defined, they're going to be defined somewhere outside of RDFa, and so if RDFa defines it own parallel list then it's going to get out of sync at some point s/it/its It sounds like Google is using it as a serialisation of a non-RDF data format, rather than of RDF (and they're using microformats as a different serialisation of the same internal non-RDF data format) b8810fee2f4a71f849f3f7409546d1d9: Kind of like cheering when Google starts using "<!doctype html>" on some of their pages? :-) It seems there's some degree of fanboyism around every technology I guess it still could be useful for each group to point out the unjustified fanboyism of each other group, even if we're all doing it It seems the kind of situation that makes self-awareness difficult, which is why it's helpful to have other people point it out (...though preferably in a way that's not too rude or condescending, I guess)

8c8837db54a2907cacd8633547977e33: I've proposed before that <legend> in <figure> should be renamed for that reason <caption> would actually be a better name but makes figures break inside tables but if we are going to consider existing browser behavior then <legend> is not good either <legend> breaks in <details> too one new title-like name would do for both of those and if it had sane parsing rules could be used for anything in the future I think failing the Degrades Gracefully design principle is a worse problem than element proliferation I believe I also suggested the existing <label> I think the only worry about <label> was that existing pages might have CSS rules that assume <label> is always a form control label so adding a <figure> would do weird things however, if that is a problem with considering, then the problem with <legend> is worth considering as well or you could just use a new element name and <figure> could be used without waiting for browser changes to be widely deployed <rubric>, <tag>, <name> are all quasi-synonyms for label/legend/caption (to ideally match english, a details control would have a label, and a figure would have a caption, sadly those two elements are the ones with issues) (though I am not sure details getting form label CSS styling on its <label> would be particularly wrong) (<legend> is actually a fruity choice of name for <fieldset> too, you wouldn't normally use <legend> in that context) er rather, you wouldn't use the word "legend" to describe a fieldset label, in, say, an HI guide <legend> is barely more semantically appropriate than <div> as I said before, you wouldn't use the word "legend" in English normally to refer to either of the new things (or to the label of a fieldset either) a map has a legend, a figure has a caption a legend is ordinarily a box on the side explaining symbols or colors form controls and UI elements don't have legends, they have headings or labels though 69b0d3dfe919a6b860a9fac82de52a7e and 14af4ca97e316b17ea96286dc6882fd4 were saying opposite things for that matter, a chart can have both a legend and a caption and they are two different things anyway Why does anyone care if browsers sniff here, again?  Other than theoretical purity?  As long as they're not interpreting non-scripted content as scripted . . . ab7faae5d7b250ea8606486575f8f79c, they can sniff on direct viewing too. Maybe we should just officially switch from MIME types to file extensions.  The latter are probably much more reliable for random files . . . Well, if every binary format chose a unique binary string to prefix the file, then sniffing would always work. It's too bad that's not a universally-accepted standard. It's not generally used for serving entirely different data formats from the same URL. Content negotiation is used by a few standards diehards as a proof-of-concept, but not actually used by any nontrivial number of production sites. I will grant that its adoption probably exceeds that of XHTML2, for example. But by any reasonable metric of success, content negotiation was and is a failure, and it should be treated as such. Yes, of course, I hate freedom.  Also puppies, and charity. It doesn't hurt anyone, but it's a failure, as a standard.  Our goal here is to come up with specs that are not failures. I just finished reading it 6ce98a4a7b6e097946960dcb1f2d404b, politely or honestly? then his suggestions are BS! like his suggestion for using <!DOCTYPE html5> won't work because that triggers quirks mode and his suggestion to upgrade that to <!DOCTYPE html6>, <!DOCTYPE html7> and into infinity totally misses the point of Don't Break the Web a924fb58d2c25874322f4e5126f608b9, those suggestions are equally silly must we be doomed to repeat the mistakes of browser sniffing? his example of the child selector html>body breaking the web when they implemented it is based on the fact that they fixed the filter, but failed to fix the significant limitations that relied on it the same applies to * html cc097e0d7183ae8436e7df709553c8c0, they didn't even fix all the major well documented limitations, which is the problem... they need to completely remove hasLayout from their standards mode, it's nonsense. He suggests we version the spec, when what he really argues for is versioning pages to a IE version There have been several suggestions like <meta ie-version-support="7"> already, which should suit his needs just fine But they at the very least attempt to solve the right problem They're willing to ship bugs, but not fixes. re: "authors will at least prohibit links directly into those images" I want to say that raising such barriers is against the nature of the web, but I'll just say it here and not mail it :) Henri, I know the arguments against <h> <l> and <separator> :), think they make sense too, it was just a p.s. of my personal opinion. Imho it's relatively easy to change and still have it work, and the naming would be better, but I don $Bc`QU (B expect it to get in HTML5.
